<section xml:id="dirichlet-characters" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Dirichlet Characters and L-Functions</title>

  <p>
    Let <m>N \in \mathbb{N}</m>. Let <m>\chi:(\mathbb{Z}/N\mathbb{Z})^{\times} \to \mathbb{C}^{\times}</m> be a primitive Dirichlet character (i.e., it does not factor through <m>(\mathbb{Z}/m\mathbb{Z})^{\times}</m> for any proper divisor <m>m</m> of <m>N</m>). We can extend <m>\chi</m> to a function <m>\chi: \Z \to \mathbb{C}</m> by setting
    <me>
      \chi(m) = \begin{cases}
      \chi(m (\mod N)) \: \text{if } (m,N) = 1\\
      0 \: \text{if } (m,N) > 1
    \end{cases}
    </me>
  </p>
  <p>
    We can define the L-function of <m>\chi</m> as follows:
  </p>
  <p>
    <m>
      L(s,\chi) = \sum_{n = 1}^{\infty} \frac{\chi(n)}{n^s} = \prod_{p} \left( 1 - \frac{\chi(p)}{p^s} \right)^{-1}
    </m>
  </p>
  <p>
    This series has two interesting properties:
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        It converges absolutely and uniformly for <m>\text{Re}(s) \geq 1 + \epsilon</m> for any fixed <m>\epsilon > 0</m>.
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        It has an analytic continuation to the entire complex plane except when <m>N = 1</m> and <m>\chi</m> is the trivial character, in which case it has a meromorphic continuation with a simple pole at <m>s = 1</m> with residue 1.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    The zeta function satisfies a few functional equations which are stated below (without proofs):
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>
          \Lambda(\chi,s) = \left(\frac{\pi}{N}\right)^{-\frac{1}{2}(s + \sigma)}\Gamma\left(\frac{1}{2}(s + \sigma)\right)L(\chi,s)
        </m>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>
          \Lambda(\chi,s) = \frac{\tau(\chi)}{i^{\sigma}N^{1/2}}\Lambda(\overline{\chi},1-s)
        </m>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    where we have
  </p>
  <p>
    <m>
      \sigma = \begin{cases}
      0 \: \text{if } \chi(-1) = 1 \\
      1 \: \text{if } \chi(-1) = -1
      \end{cases}
    </m>
  </p>
  <p>
    and the Gauss sum
  </p>
  <p>
    <m>\tau(\chi) = \sum_{m = 1}^N \chi(m) e^{\frac{2\pi i m}{N}}</m> (Gauss sum)
  </p>
  <p>
    and clearly <m>|\tau(\chi)| = \sqrt{N}</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    As a consequence we have
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>L(\chi,1-n) = 0 \quad \text{if} \quad \chi(-1) \neq (-1)^n</m>
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>L(\chi,1 - n) \neq 0 \quad \text{if} \quad \chi(-1) = (-1)^n</m>
      </p>
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    where <m>n \in \mathbb{N}</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    An important fact relating L-functions to Bernoulli numbers is:
  </p>
  <p>
    For <m>n \geq 0</m> and <m>\chi(-1) = (-1)^n</m> we have
    <m>L(\chi,1-n) = -\frac{B_{n,\chi}}{n}</m> where
  </p>
  <p>
    <m>
      \sum_{n = 0}^{\infty} \frac{B_{n,\chi}}{n!}t^n = \sum_{a = 1}^{N} \frac{\chi(a)te^{at}}{e^{Nt} - 1}
    </m>
    (Formal identity)
  </p>
  <p>
    In particular, <m>L(\chi,1-n) \in \mathbb{Q}(\chi)</m>, the field obtained by adjoining the values of <m>\chi</m> to <m>\mathbb{Q}</m>, so we end up with algebraic numbers.
  </p>

  <subsection>
    <title>An Important Example</title>
    <p>
      For <m>\chi(-1) = -1</m>, we have
      <m>L(\chi,0) = -\frac{1}{N}\sum_{a = 1}^{N} \chi(a)a</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      This is since if we consider <m>F(s) = \sum_{n = 1}^{\infty} a_nn^{-s}</m> converges for <m>\text{Re}(s) > 0</m> and <m>A(x) = \sum_{n \leq x} a_n </m> then we have
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>
        \begin{aligned}
        F(s) \amp= s \int_{1}^{\infty} A(x)x^{-s-1}dx \\
        \amp= s \int_{1}^{\infty} (B - (A(x) - B))x^{-s-1} dx \\
        \amp= B + \int_{1}^{\infty}(A(x) - B)x^{-s-1} dx
        \end{aligned}
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Now if we let <m>A(x)</m> to be <m>q</m>-periodic and we choose <m>B = \frac{1}{N}\int_{0}^{N} A(x)dx</m> then
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>
        \begin{align*}
        F(0) \amp= B \\
        \amp= \frac{1}{N} \int_{0}^{N} A(x)dx \\
        \amp= \frac{1}{N} \sum_{a = 1}^{N} (N - a)a_n \\
        \amp= \frac{1}{N} \sum_{a = 1}^{N} Na_n - \frac{1}{N}\sum_{a = 1}^{N} aa_n \\
        \amp= -\frac{1}{N} \sum_{a = 1}^{N} aa_n \:\:\: (\text{due to periodicity})
        \end{align*}
      </m>
    </p>
    <p>
      Following this we choose <m>F(s) = L(s,\chi)</m> and <m>a_n = \chi(n)</m> and using the above we get
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>L(0,\chi) = -\frac{1}{N} \sum_{a = 1}^{N} a\chi(a)</m>
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection>
    <title>Another Example</title>
    <p>
      Let <m>p</m> be an odd prime, <m>\zeta_p</m> a primitive <m>p^{\text{th}}</m>-root of unity.
    </p>
    <p>
      We know that
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>G = \text{Gal}(\mathbb{Q}(\zeta_p)/\mathbb{Q}) \cong (\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z})^{\times}</m> where the map is such that <m>\sigma \longmapsto a</m>, with <m>\sigma(\zeta_p) = \zeta_p^a</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      There exists an embedding
      <me>
        \begin{CD}
(\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z})^{\times} @>>> \mathbb{Z}_p^{\times} \\
@VVV @AAA \\
\mu_{p-1} @= \mu_{p-1}
\end{CD}

      </me>
      where <m>\mu_{p - 1}</m> is the set of <m>p-1</m> roots of unity, the top arrow and the right arrows are inclusions and the left arrow is an isomorphism. 
      The map <m>\omega: G \cong (\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z})^{\times} \to   \mathbb{Z}_p^{\times}</m> is the Teichmuller lift. The map from <m>\mu_{p - 1} \to \mathbb{Z}_p^{\times}</m> is due to Hensel's Lemma, which is as follows
    </p>
    <p>
      <theorem>
        <title>Hensel's Lemma</title>
        <creator>Kurt Hensel</creator>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>f(x) \in \mathbb{Z}[x]</m> be a polynomial such that <m>f(a) \equiv 0 \mod p</m> for some <m>a \in \mathbb{Z}</m>. If <m>f'(a) \not\equiv 0 \mod p</m>, then there exists a unique <m>b \in \mathbb{Z}_p</m> such that <m>f(b) = 0</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </theorem> 
      By this we know that any solution to <m>x^{p^{n - 1}} \equiv 0 \mod p</m> can be lifted to a unique solution in <m>\mathbb{Z}_p</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Let <m>\widehat{G}</m> be the dual of <m>G</m>, this can be identified with <m>\{\omega^i \mid 0 \leq i \leq p - 2\}</m>. We denote <m>H_p</m> be the maximal unramified <m>p</m>-extension of <m>\mathbb{Q}(\zeta_p)</m>, i.e <m>\text{Gal}(H_p/\mathbb{Q}(\zeta_p)) = p^k</m> for some <m>k \geq 0</m>. Diagramatically, 
    </p>
    <p>
      <me>
        \begin{CD}
H_p \\
@VVV \\
\mathbb{Q}(\zeta_p) \\
@VV{G}V \\
\mathbb{Q}
\end{CD}
      </me>
      
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>\text{Gal}(H_p/\mathbb{Q}_p)</m> is acted upon by <m>G</m> by conjugation and by <m>\mathbb{Z}_p</m> since it is a finite abelian <m>p</m>-group. Thus it is a <m>\mathbb{Z}_p[G]</m>-module. Let <m>A = \text{Gal}(H_p/\mathbb{Q}(\zeta_p))</m>. 
    </p>
    <theorem>
      <title>Class Field Theory</title>
      
      
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>A \cong p</m>-Sylow subgroup of the class group of <m>\mathbb{Q}(\zeta_p)</m>, since it is a <m>p</m>-group and necessarily contained in the class group since it is unramified.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
      We have 
      <me>
        \epsilon_i = \frac{1}{p - 1}\sum_{a = 1}^{p - 1} \omega^i(a)\sigma_a^{-1} \in \mathbb{Z}_p[[G]]
      </me>
      We have <m>\epsilon_i^2 = \epsilon_i, \:\: \epsilon_i\epsilon_j = 0, \:\: \sigma_a \longleftrightarrow a</m> under <m>G \to (\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z})^{\times}</m> 
    </p>
    <p>
      We have <m>A = \oplus_{i = 0}^{p - 2} A_i, \:\: A_i = \epsilon_i A</m>(<m>\omega_i</m>-isotypical piece of <m>A</m>) i.e, <m>v \in A_i</m>, <m>\sigma_a(v) = \omega^i(a)v</m> 
    </p>
    <theorem>
      <statement>
        <p>
          <m>\lvert A_i \rvert = p-</m>part of the Bernoulli number <m>B_{1,\omega^{-i}} = p-</m>part of <m>L(\omega^{-i},0)</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>
    <p>
    As <m>L</m>-values <m>L(\chi,1-n)</m> are related to orders of pieces of class groups.
    </p>
  </subsection>

</section>